Thanks for the detailed report and sample file!

The `SKCodec.EncodedOrigin` property directly returns the value from Skia's native RAW codec. Since ExifTool correctly reads the orientation as `LeftBottom` (Rotate 270 CW), the issue is that Skia's RAW codec isn't parsing the EXIF orientation tag from Canon CR2 files — it falls back to `TopLeft` (the default).

This appears to be a limitation in the upstream Skia native RAW codec rather than in the SkiaSharp C# bindings.

**Workaround:** Use the [MetadataExtractor](https://www.nuget.org/packages/MetadataExtractor) NuGet package to read the EXIF orientation independently:

```csharp
using MetadataExtractor;
using MetadataExtractor.Formats.Exif;

var directories = ImageMetadataReader.ReadMetadata(source.FullName);
var exifDir = directories.OfType<ExifIfd0Directory>().FirstOrDefault();
int orientation = exifDir?.GetInt32(ExifDirectoryBase.TagOrientation) ?? 1;
// Map EXIF orientation (1-8) to your rotation logic
```

We'll investigate whether this can be fixed in the native Skia RAW codec.
